Paris is known as the "City of Light," a title it earned during the Age of Enlightenment and because it was one of the first cities to adopt street lighting.
The Eiffel Tower, built by Gustave Eiffel for the 1889 Exposition Universelle, is one of the most recognizable landmarks in the world and a symbol of Paris.
Paris is renowned for its world-class museums, including the Louvre, which houses thousands of works of art, including the Mona Lisa and the Venus de Milo.
The Seine River runs through the heart of Paris, with many historical bridges connecting the city's left and right banks.
Parisian cuisine is celebrated globally, featuring delicacies like croissants, escargot, and a wide variety of cheeses and wines.
Every year, Paris Fashion Week gathers fashion enthusiasts from around the world, showcasing the latest trends from top designers.
The Notre-Dame Cathedral, a masterpiece of French Gothic architecture, is one of the most visited sites in Paris.
Montmartre, known for its artistic history, is home to the Sacré-Cœur Basilica and offers some of the best views of the city.
Paris has a significant literary history, having been home to famous writers such as Ernest Hemingway, Gertrude Stein, and James Joyce during the 1920s.
The city's public transport system, including the Metro, buses, and RER trains, is an extensive network that facilitates easy exploration of the city's numerous arrondissements.
